@Reasoning:
Statement classification is keyword-driven for directives (if*/include/export/define/override) but requires lookahead-1 for identifier-prefixed lines because "VAR = value" and "target: deps" both start with TOKEN_IDENTIFIER. The lookahead checks the assignment-operator family vs colon to discriminate; unknown statement lines fall through to skip-to-newline so parser recovery is bounded.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
The dispatch order matters: conditionals and directives must be checked before identifier-based dispatch because some directives (PHONY, SUFFIXES) might otherwise be confused with target identifiers. Special targets are routed to parse_target_rule because they share rule syntax with regular targets.
@End Implementation
Process called "parse_statement" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    proc skip_newlines from parser_ptr

    Let is_end be proc is_at_end from parser_ptr
    If is_end is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_ptr be proc current_token from parser_ptr
    Let token_type be proc read_integer from Memory with token_ptr, 0

    Note: Conditionals
    If token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_IFEQ or token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_IFNEQ or token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_IFDEF or token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_IFNDEF:
        Let node_ptr be proc parse_conditional from parser_ptr
        Return node_ptr
    End If

    Note: Directives
    If token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_INCLUDE or token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_SINCLUDE or token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_DASH_INCLUDE:
        Set node_ptr to proc parse_include_directive from parser_ptr
        Return node_ptr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_EXPORT or token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_UNEXPORT:
        Set node_ptr to proc parse_export_directive from parser_ptr
        Return node_ptr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_DEFINE:
        Set node_ptr to proc parse_define_block from parser_ptr
        Return node_ptr
    End If

    If token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_OVERRIDE:
        Set node_ptr to proc parse_variable_assignment from parser_ptr
        Return node_ptr
    End If

    Note: Check for special targets (.PHONY, etc.)
    If token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_PHONY or token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_SUFFIXES or token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_DEFAULT:
        Note: Parse as target rule (special targets are just rules)
        Set node_ptr to proc parse_target_rule from parser_ptr
        Return node_ptr
    End If

    Note: Identifier could be variable assignment or target rule
    If token_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Note: Look ahead to determine which it is
        Let next_token_ptr be proc peek_token with parser_ptr, 1
        If next_token_ptr is not equal to 0:
            Let next_type be proc read_integer from Memory with next_token_ptr, 0

            Note: Assignment operators
            If next_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_ASSIGN or next_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_IMMEDIATE_ASSIGN or next_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_APPEND_ASSIGN or next_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_CONDITIONAL_ASSIGN:
                Set node_ptr to proc parse_variable_assignment from parser_ptr
                Return node_ptr
            End If

            Note: Colon indicates target rule
            If next_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_COLON or next_type is equal to MakefileLexer.TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON:
                Set node_ptr to proc parse_target_rule from parser_ptr
                Return node_ptr
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Unknown statement - skip line
    proc consume_until_newline from parser_ptr
    proc skip_newlines from parser_ptr
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The top-level parse loop iterates parse_statement until end-of-tokens; each statement is appended to the root's statements list. We check has_error after each parse_statement returning 0 so the loop exits immediately on a fatal error rather than spinning on an unrecoverable position; non-zero returns keep parsing because the root AST should aggregate as many recoverable statements as possible.
@End Reasoning
Process called "parse_makefile" that takes parser_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let root_ptr be proc allocate from Memory with 32
    proc write_integer from Memory with root_ptr, 0, NODE_MAKEFILE

    Let statements_list be proc create_list from ListCore
    proc write_integer from Memory with root_ptr, 8, statements_list
    proc write_integer from Memory with root_ptr, 16, 1  Note: line_number
    proc write_integer from Memory with root_ptr, 24, 1  Note: column_number

    Note: Parse all statements
    Let continue be 1
    While continue is equal to 1:
        proc skip_newlines from parser_ptr

        Let is_end be proc is_at_end from parser_ptr
        If is_end is equal to 1:
            Set continue to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let statement_ptr be proc parse_statement from parser_ptr
            If statement_ptr is equal to 0:
                Let has_error be proc read_integer from Memory with parser_ptr, 24
                If has_error is equal to 1:
                    Return 0
                End If
            Otherwise:
                proc add_to_list from ListCore with statements_list, statement_ptr
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return root_ptr
End Process
